<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-549-767  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 549 767.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 29 1990 v7 n44 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users paying big price for PBX fraud.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Several companies are suffering losses of more than $700,000 infraudulent phone charges.andP;  Hustlers are running call-selloperations where they tap into firms' PBXs and sell phone serviceat discount rates.andP;  One type of PBX fraud concerns the DirectInward System Access (DISA) feature.andP;  Corporate employees use thefeature to dial into the PBX via an 800 number.andP;  They then enteran access code and receive an outside line.andP;  Call-sell operatorswho get hold of the DISA codes and 800 numbers are able tooriginate calls through a firm's PBX, with all calls gettingcharged to the company.andP;  Companies must pay for the calls becausethey are validated and set up by the PBXs instead of carrierswitches.andP;  PBX fraud has been on the rise due to long-distancecarriers getting tougher on calls made with stolen calling cards.andO;Seventy to eighty percent of fraudulent calls originate from NewYork.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FraudPBXTelephone CompaniesLosses.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>